# TypeScript Conventions

## Strict Mode

`tsconfig.json` enables `strict`, `exactOptionalPropertyTypes`, `noUncheckedIndexedAccess`. Respect them:

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — noUncheckedIndexedAccess: bracket access returns T | undefined
const id = req.params['id']; // string | undefined
const user = await service.getUser(id); // TS error: string | undefined ≠ string

// ✅ GOOD — null-check before use
const id = req.params['id'];
if (id == null || Array.isArray(id)) throw new BadRequestError('ID required');
const user = await service.getUser(id); // id is now narrowed to string
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — exactOptionalPropertyTypes: optional props cannot receive `undefined` implicitly
const data: { firstName?: string } = { firstName: someValue }; // error if someValue can be undefined

// ✅ GOOD — only assign if the value is actually defined
const data: { firstName?: string } = {};
if (someValue !== undefined) data.firstName = someValue;
```

## Naming

- Interfaces: prefix with `I` → `IUser`, `IJwtPayload`, `IUserDocument`, `IUserModel`
- DTO types: PascalCase with `Dto` suffix → `RegisterUserDto`, `UpdateUserDto`
- Files: kebab-case → `user.service.ts`, `auth.middleware.ts`, `cache.service.ts`
- Every directory gets a barrel `index.ts`

## Imports

- Always use `.js` extension: `import { env } from '../../config/index.js'`
- Import order: `node:` builtins → external packages → internal (`@/`, `../`, `./`)
- Use `import type` for type-only imports

## Errors

- Always throw `AppError` subclasses, never raw `Error`
- Hierarchy in `src/shared/errors/app-error.ts`: `BadRequestError` (400), `UnauthorizedError` (401), `ForbiddenError` (403), `NotFoundError` (404), `ConflictError` (409), `ValidationError` (422), `TooManyRequestsError` (429)

## Responses

- Always use `ResponseHelper.success()` / `.error()` / `.created()` / `.noContent()`
- Never call `res.json()` or `res.send()` directly in controllers

## Async Handlers

- The `authenticate` middleware is async — always wrap it: `asyncHandler(authenticate)`
- All controller methods are async — always wrap them: `asyncHandler((req, res) => ctrl.method(req, res))`
